sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K258002
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Granulysin, a T Cell Product,Kills Bacteria by Altering Membrane Permeability
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Ozkan IS
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Granulysin, a protein located in the acidic granules of human NK cells and cytotoxic T cells, has microbial activity against a broad spectrum of microbial pathogens. The substance released by cytotoxic T cells (CD8) when attached to infected body cells. It creates holes in the target cell membrane and destroy it. That is,Granulysin induces apoptosis in target cells and have antimicrobial action. It is broadly antimicrobial, killing microbes that cause, for example, tuberculosis and malaria, and can destroy some tumors. A series of peptides generated from the amino acid sequence of granulysin are potential antibiotics. Granulysin increased the permeability of bacterial membranes, as judged by its ability to allow access of cytosolic ??-galactosidase to its impermeant substrate.Granulysin functions to create holes in the target cell membrane and destroy it. Granulysin is able to induce apoptosis in target cells and also has antimicrobial action.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: Granulysin can be purified via nickel affinity chromatography.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Granulysin is a member of the saposin-like protein (SAPLIP) family. The gene was synthesized at GENEART in pMA vector

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Tomoki Uchino
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This part codes anti-Norovirus GII.4 scFv (single-chain variable fragment) which derives from human 12A2 antibody. This scFv is suggested to prevent binding of human norovirus to Hist-Blood Group Antigens. [1] This coding sequence was fused to INPNC-His (part number: ) or BclA-His (part number: ) in our project. For more information, please visit our Wiki page.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: silent mutation was made to remove PstI: G255C
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: We have been given given the scFv-encoding plasmid (NoV GII.4 strain-specific antibody 12A2 (vector: pSCCA5-E8d)) from Dr. Kyoko Moriguchi of the Fujita Health University Department of Virology Parasitology.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K133046
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Ana Lasic
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
This is a part that is composed of C-terminal end of chimeric flagellin (BBa_K133016). We used aminoacids from 215th aminoacid on.
Chimeric flagellin is composed of C- and N-terminal part of E.coli flagellin and of variable region of H.pylori. The E.coli parts are responsible for binding and activation of cell membrane receptor TLR5 to initiate immune response, while H.pylori variable region was used to array the immune response against H.pylori.
This part was used in combination with CF213 - chimeric flagellin (BBa_K133010). Between the CF213 and CF215 we have put H.pylori antigens in order to array the immune response against H.pylori.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: It was important to split the chimeric flagellin in the variable region to assure that the antigen will be in the right place and not to interrupt the 3d structure of the protein.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: We used polimerase chain reaction from chimeric flagellin (BBa_K133016).
